3. Why Do We Even Use ORM?
Before ORM, developers wrote 
.........................


plain JDBC code. You'd manually create a connection, write SQL strings,
execute them, loop through ResultSets, and map each column to a Java field by hand. It worked - but it was
tedious, error-prone, and full of boilerplate.
Here's a rough idea of what that looked like:
// Without ORM - old school JDBC
Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);
PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(
 "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?"
);
ps.setLong(1, userId);
ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();
if (rs.next()) {
 User user = new User();
 user.setId(rs.getLong("id"));
 user.setName(rs.getString("name"));
 user.setEmail(rs.getString("email"));
}
// ... close everything manually. Don't forget or you'll leak connections.
Now compare that to what JPA gives you:
// With JPA + Spring Data


User user = userRepository.findById(userId).orElseThrow();
// That's it. One line.



ORM doesn't remove SQL from your life completely. It hides it. For complex queries, you still need to
understand SQL - JPA just handles the boring CRUD for you.


