6. @Id and @GeneratedValue - The Primary Key Story

...............

Every entity needs a primary key. That's not a JPA rule - that's a database rule. @Id tells JPA which field is the
primary key. Simple enough.

The interesting part is @GeneratedValue. This tells JPA how the primary key value should be generated. You
don't want to assign IDs manually 

GenerationType.             AUTO JPA picks the strategy based on the database. Default option but unpredictable
                            across DBs.
GenerationType.IDENTITY     Uses the database's auto-increment. Most common choice for MySQL and
                            PostgreSQL.
GenerationType.SEQUENCE     Uses a DB sequence object. Common in Oracle and PostgreSQL for
                            performance reasons.
GenerationType.TABLE        Uses a separate table to track ID values. Rarely used. Slow. Avoid in most
                              cases


For most beginner and intermediate projects - especially ones using MySQL - you'll see
GenerationType.IDENTITY. This tells the database to handle the auto-increment. 

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)


7. Entity Lifecycle - Keep It Simple for Now
This is a topic that can go very deep - but for fresher-level interviews, you just need the basic picture. A JPA
entity can be in one of four states at any given time:
• Transient: The object exists in Java memory but JPA doesn't know about it. You just did new
Product() and haven't saved it yet.
• Managed (Persistent): JPA is tracking this object. Any changes you make to it will automatically be
saved to the database when the transaction commits. This is the state after
entityManager.persist() or after loading from a repository.
• Detached: The object was managed, but the persistence context closed (session ended). Changes to it
won't be saved automatically.
• Removed: Marked for deletion. Will be deleted from the database when the transaction commits.

