9. How It All Connects - The Full Picture
.............
ing Boot reads application.properties
 → Gets the DB URL, username, password
2. Spring Boot creates a DataSource (connection pool via HikariCP by default)
 → Manages a pool of database connections so we're not creating one per request
3. Hibernate scans for @Entity classes
 → Finds Product, User, Order etc. and maps them to tables
4. Hibernate applies ddl-auto strategy
 → Creates, updates, or validates the schema
5. Spring Data JPA creates Repository implementations
 → UserRepository, ProductRepository etc. are ready to use
6. Your app is up. Requests come in, repositories do their job.


INTERVIEW QUESTION
How does Spring Boot connect to a database? Walk me through it.
..........................

How to answer: Spring Boot reads the datasource configuration from application.properties - the URL,
credentials, and driver. It creates a DataSource bean backed by HikariCP as the connection pool. Hibernate
then scans for @Entity classes and maps them to database tables. Spring Data JPA generates repository
implementations on top of that. 





3. The N+1 Query Problem
.............................
...............................
you load 10 users. For each user, JPA lazily fetches their orders. That is 1 query to get the users, then 10 more
queries to get each user's orders. 11 queries total instead of 1. With 100 users it becomes 101 queries.
This happens silently. Your code looks clean. The SQL log (show-sql=true) tells the real story. Under any
real load, this kind of query pattern will be noticeable.
The fix: use JOIN FETCH in a JPQL query or annotate your repository method with @EntityGraph. Both tell
JPA to load the users and their orders in a single query

// N+1 problem - one extra query per user
List<User> users = userRepository.findAll();
users.forEach(u -> System.out.println(u.getOrders())); // triggers N queries
// Fix with JOIN FETCH
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u JOIN FETCH u.orders")
List<User> findAllWithOrders();